'''Shioya Hachiman-gū''' (塩屋八幡宮) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Yatsushiro, Kumamoto|ja|八代市|12=draft}}, Kumamoto Prefecture, Japan. Under the former {{ill|Modern shrine ranking system|ja|近代社格制度|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|12=draft}}, it was classified as a village shrine (村社).

== History ==

In 1632 ({{ill|Kan'ei|ja|寛永|12=draft}} 9), {{ill|Hosokawa Tadaoki|ja|細川忠興|12=draft}} (Sansai) retired to {{ill|Yatsushiro Castle|ja|八代城|12=draft}} and, as part of his reverence for {{ill|Usa Jingū|ja|宇佐神宮|12=draft}}, he enshrined its deity at Hachiman-hama (present-day Wakamiya Shrine).<ref>From Shioya Hachiman-gū's historical documents.</ref>

In 1655 ({{ill|Meireki|ja|明暦|12=draft}} 1), {{ill|Matsui Okinaga|ja|松井興長|12=draft}} relocated the shrine to its current site, establishing it as the guardian shrine of the western region of Yatsushiro's castle town. The shrine serves as the sacred resting place for the procession of the {{ill|Myōken Festival|ja|妙見祭|12=draft}}, one of the three major festivals in Kyushu, associated with {{ill|Yatsushiro Shrine|ja|八代神社|12=draft}}.<ref>Edited and published by Kumamoto Nichinichi Shimbun, "Kumamoto Prefecture Encyclopedia," 1982, p. 398.</ref>

== Enshrined Deities ==

* {{ill|Emperor Ōjin|ja|応神天皇|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Empress Jingū|ja|神功皇后|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Emperor Nintoku|ja|仁徳天皇|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Takeuchi no Sukune|ja|武内宿禰|12=draft}}

== festival ==
* November 25

== Sub-Shrines ==

* {{ill|Kompira Shrine|ja|金刀比羅宮|1=Kotohira-gū|12=draft}}
** Enshrined deities: {{ill|Ōmononushi|ja|大物主|12=draft}}, {{ill|Emperor Sutoku|ja|崇徳天皇|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Inari Shrine|ja|稲荷神社|12=draft}}
** Enshrined deities: {{ill|Ukanomitama|ja|倉稲魂神|12=draft}}, {{ill|Sarutahiko|ja|猿田彦命|12=draft}}, Ōmiyame-no-Mikoto

