== History ==

In 1632 ({{ill|Kan'ei|ja|寛永|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 9), {{ill|Hosokawa Tadaoki|ja|細川忠興|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Sansai) retired to {{ill|Yatsushiro Castle|ja|八代城|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and, as part of his reverence for {{ill|Usa Jingū|ja|宇佐神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, he enshrined its deity at Hachiman-hama (present-day Wakamiya Shrine).<ref>From Shioya Hachiman-gū's historical documents.</ref>

In 1655 ({{ill|Meireki|ja|明暦|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 1), {{ill|Matsui Okinaga|ja|松井興長|qq=draft|qq=draft}} relocated the shrine to its current site, establishing it as the guardian shrine of the western region of Yatsushiro's castle town. The shrine serves as the sacred resting place for the procession of the {{ill|Myōken Festival|ja|妙見祭|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, one of the three major festivals in Kyushu, associated with {{ill|Yatsushiro Shrine|ja|八代神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref>Edited and published by Kumamoto Nichinichi Shimbun, "Kumamoto Prefecture Encyclopedia," 1982, p. 398.</ref>

