'''Shioya Hachiman-gū''' (塩屋八幡宮) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinto shrine|qq=}} located in {{ill|Yatsushiro, Kumamoto|ja|八代市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yatsushiro, Kumamoto|qq=}}, Kumamoto Prefecture, Japan. Under the former {{ill|Modern shrine Ranking system|ja|近代社格制度|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|1=Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Modern shrine Ranking system|13=User:Immanuelle/Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|qq=}}, it was classified as a village shrine (村社).

== History ==

In 1632 ({{ill|Kan'ei|ja|寛永|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kan'ei|qq=}} 9), {{ill|Hosokawa Tadaoki|ja|細川忠興|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hosokawa Tadaoki|qq=}} (Sansai) retired to {{ill|Yatsushiro Castle|ja|八代城|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yatsushiro Castle|qq=}} and, as part of his reverence for {{ill|Usa Jingū|ja|宇佐神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Usa Jingū|qq=}}, he enshrined its deity at Hachiman-hama (present-day Wakamiya Shrine).<ref>From Shioya Hachiman-gū's historical documents.</ref>

In 1655 ({{ill|Meireki|ja|明暦|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meireki|qq=}} 1), {{ill|Matsui Okinaga|ja|松井興長|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Matsui Okinaga|qq=}} relocated the shrine to its current site, establishing it as the guardian shrine of the western region of Yatsushiro's castle town. The shrine serves as the sacred resting place for the procession of the {{ill|Myōken Festival|ja|妙見祭|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Myōken Festival|qq=}}, one of the three major festivals in Kyushu, associated with {{ill|Yatsushiro Shrine|ja|八代神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yatsushiro Shrine|qq=}}.<ref>Edited and published by Kumamoto Nichinichi Shimbun, "Kumamoto Prefecture Encyclopedia," 1982, p. 398.</ref>

== Enshrined Deities ==

